","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1259":"1259","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1253":"1253","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1259–1310":"1259–1310","1253–1306":"1253–1306","1290–1385":"1290–1385","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1259":"1259","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1253":"1253","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Carrick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): habitational name from Carrick, a steep and rocky district in Ayrshire, named in Old Welsh with <i>carreg</i> ‘rock’, borrowed into Gaelic as <i>carraig</i>.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarrick  .","History: The earliest bearers of the Scottish Carrick surname (see 1 above) were descendants of the 12th-century lords of Galloway who became earls of Carrick in the early 13th century. The earldom passed by marriage to the   Bruce   family in later in the 13th century and then to the crown with the succession of Robert Bruce, earl of Carrick, to the throne in 1306. Illegitimate descendants of the earliest earls, themselves noblemen, continued to use the Carrick surname."],"variants":[{"name":"McCarrick","meanings":["Irish and Scottish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Con Charraige</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Charraige</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the rock’.","Anglicized form of <b>Mac Con Chathrach</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Chathrach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the fort’."]},{"name":"Corrick","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Carrick   or <b>Carrack</b>, a habitational name probably from Castle Carrock (Cumbria), which is earlier recorded as <i>Castel Carok</i>. The placename derives from British <i>castello-</i> ‘castle, camp’ (a borrowing from Latin <i>castellum</i> ‘fort’) + a word related to Welsh <i>caerog</i> ‘fortified’."]},{"name":"Karrick","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carrick   1.","Possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   McCarrick  . Compare   Carrick   2.","Americanized form of German <b>Karrich</b>: metonymic occupational name for a carter or cartwright, from Middle High German <i>karrech</i> ‘cart’, from Latin <i>carruca</i>. The surname <i>Karrick</i> is very rare in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary De Carrick was born in 1259, in Scotland as the daughter of Unknown and Unknown. She had at least 1 son with Gilbert Fitz Roland. She died in 1310, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1259–1310":"1259–1310","1253–1306":"1253–1306","1290–1385":"1290–1385","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1259":"1259","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1253":"1253","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1259–1310":"1259–1310","1253–1306":"1253–1306","1290–13